1. Kawasaki disease: This is a rare inflammatory disease that primarily affects young children. It can cause fever, skin rash, swollen lymph nodes, and inflammation of the blood vessels. While other symptoms like conjunctivitis and strawberry tongue are more common, foot edema, maculopapular rash, leukocytosis, and lip cracking can also occur.

2. Drug reaction with eosinophilia and systemic symptoms (DRESS): This is a severe allergic reaction to certain medications that can cause a variety of symptoms, including fever, rash, swollen lymph nodes, and organ damage. Foot edema, maculopapular rash, leukocytosis, and lip cracking are all possible symptoms of DRESS.

3. Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE): This is a chronic autoimmune disease that can affect many different parts of the body. Symptoms can vary widely from person to person, but may include fever, rash, joint pain, fatigue, and kidney problems. Foot edema, maculopapular rash, leukocytosis, and lip cracking can all be seen in SLE.

4. Henoch-Schonlein purpura (HSP): This is a blood vessel inflammation condition that mainly affects children. It causes a purple rash, joint pain, abdominal pain, and kidney problems. While gastrointestinal issues are frequent, other symptoms include foot edema, maculopapular rash, leukocytosis, and lip cracking.

5. Infectious mononucleosis: This is a common viral infection that is often spread through saliva. Symptoms include fever, fatigue, sore throat, swollen lymph nodes, and an enlarged spleen. Foot edema, maculopapular rash, leukocytosis, and lip cracking are less common but possible symptoms.

6. Serum sickness: This is an immune reaction to a foreign protein, such as a medication or a vaccine. It can cause fever, rash, joint pain, and swollen lymph nodes. Foot edema, maculopapular rash, leukocytosis, and lip cracking can occur in serum sickness.

7. Lymphoma: This is a type of cancer that affects the lymph nodes. Symptoms can include swollen lymph nodes, fever, weight loss, and fatigue. Foot edema, maculopapular rash, and leukocytosis can occur in some types of lymphoma.

8. Leukemia: This is a type of cancer that affects the blood and bone marrow. Symptoms can include fever, fatigue, bruising, and bleeding. Foot edema and lip cracking can be seen in some types of leukemia, although less frequent than other symptoms.

9. T-cell large granular lymphocyte leukemia: This is a rare type of leukemia that affects T cells. Symptoms can include fever, fatigue, weight loss, and skin problems. Foot edema and lip cracking are possible, but not usual.

10. Polyarteritis nodosa: This is a rare inflammatory disease that affects medium-sized arteries. It can cause fever, rash, muscle pain, and nerve damage. While other symptoms are more frequent, foot edema and leukocytosis can occur in polyarteritis nodosa.
